{
  "text": "and corresponds roughly to the condition that m be smaller than the number of wavelengths \u03bb n fitting in the perimeter. The same requirement (with refractive index n = 1) appears naturally in the 2D surface model. Apart from it we again observe the shift of all curves to the right, a cut-off phenomenon known from the cylindrical rod [CITATION_1] . This cutoff seems to disappear for m = 1. This is reminiscent of the fact that for a rod the cut-off is nonexistent for the so called HE 11 mode. The additional curves in the form of closed loops never cross the line (2.11) and therefore do not correspond to any mode. In fact they can be eliminated if one exploits (2.11) in the equation det M H = 0, before drawing the latter.",
